#set text(font: "Arial")

- *Figure 5-1:* Germ-line cells and somatic cells carry out fundamentally different functions. In sexually reproducing organisms, genetic information is propagated into the next generation exclusively by germ-line cells, which include the specialized reproductive cells (gametes). The zygote formed after fertilization gives rise to both germ-line cells and somatic cells; only germ-line cells transmit DNA to the next generation.
- *Figure 5-2:* DNA acts as a template for its own replication. Because A pairs only with T and G pairs only with C, each strand of a DNA double helix—labeled S strand and its complement S′—can serve as a template to specify the sequence of nucleotides in a complementary new strand, illustrating the molecular basis of heredity.
- *Figure 5-3:* The chemistry of DNA synthesis. Nucleotides enter the reaction as deoxyribonucleoside triphosphates; the addition of a deoxyribonucleotide to the 3′ end of a polynucleotide chain is the fundamental reaction by which DNA is synthesized, releasing pyrophosphate and requiring a free 3′-OH group.
- *Figure 5-4:* How DNA polymerase adds a deoxyribonucleotide to the end of a growing DNA strand. An incoming deoxynucleoside triphosphate forms a base pair with its partner in the template strand and is then covalently attached to the free 3′-OH end; the new DNA strand is always synthesized in the 5′-to-3′ direction.
- *Figure 5-5:* In each round of DNA replication, each of the two strands of DNA is used as a template for the formation of a new, complementary strand. DNA replication is semiconservative because each daughter DNA double helix is composed of one conserved (old) strand and one newly synthesized strand.
- *Figure 5-6:* Two replication forks moving in opposite directions on the E. coli chromosome, a large circular DNA molecule. Each replication fork has a Y-shaped structure and moves progressively along the DNA, spinning out newly replicated DNA behind it. This autoradiograph from Cairns (1963) was the first direct evidence for bidirectional replication from a single origin.
- *Figure 5-7:* At each replication fork, the lagging DNA strand is synthesized in pieces. Because both new strands must be synthesized in the 5′-to-3′ direction, the lagging strand is made discontinuously as short Okazaki fragments that are later joined, while the leading strand is synthesized continuously.
- *Figure 5-8:* During DNA synthesis, DNA polymerase proofreads its own work. If an incorrect nucleotide is accidentally added to a growing strand, the DNA polymerase stops, cleaves it from the strand using its 3′-to-5′ exonuclease activity, and replaces it with the correct nucleotide before continuing.
- *Figure 5-9:* DNA polymerase contains separate sites for DNA synthesis and proofreading. The enzyme cradles the DNA molecule being replicated and can switch between a polymerizing mode and an editing (proofreading) mode; the catalytic sites for polymerization (P) and editing (E) are shown.
- *Figure 5-10:* RNA primers are synthesized by an RNA polymerase called DNA primase, which uses a DNA strand as a template. Unlike DNA polymerase, primase can start a new chain de novo and synthesizes short RNA primers that provide the free 3′-OH end required by DNA polymerase.
- *Figure 5-11:* Different enzymes act in series to synthesize DNA on the lagging strand. In eukaryotes, RNA primers are made at intervals of about 200 nucleotides on the lagging strand; each primer is extended by DNA polymerases, then the RNA is removed and replaced with DNA, and finally the resulting Okazaki fragments are joined by DNA ligase.
- *Figure 5-12:* DNA ligase joins together Okazaki fragments on the lagging strand during DNA synthesis. The ligase enzyme uses a molecule of ATP to activate the 5′ phosphate of one fragment before forming a new phosphodiester bond with the 3′ hydroxyl of the adjacent fragment.
- *Figure 5-13:* How DNA helicase enzymes can separate strands as they move along a DNA single strand. An experiment demonstrates that purified DNA helicase acts as a "moving wedge," using the energy of ATP hydrolysis to break the hydrogen bonds between the two strands and separate them ahead of the replication fork.
- *Figure 5-14:* The structure of a DNA helicase. The protein is a hexameric ring drawn to scale with a replication fork; six identical subunits bind and hydrolyze ATP in an ordered fashion to propel the ring along one strand of the DNA double helix, unwinding the duplex as it moves.
- *Figure 5-15:* The effect of single-strand DNA-binding proteins (SSB proteins) on the structure of single-stranded DNA. Because each protein molecule prefers to bind next to a previously bound molecule, long rows form cooperatively on a DNA single strand, straightening out the DNA template and keeping it in an extended conformation for efficient replication.
- *Figure 5-16:* Human single-strand binding protein (RPA) bound to DNA. The two DNA-binding domains cover a total of eight nucleotides, with the DNA bases remaining exposed in the protein–DNA complex; the three-dimensional structure shows how RPA stabilizes single-stranded DNA without blocking base-pairing.
- *Figure 5-17:* The sliding clamp that holds DNA polymerase on the DNA. The ring-shaped clamp protein encircles the DNA and acts as a mobile platform that tethers DNA polymerase to the template, dramatically increasing processivity; the clamp loader uses ATP hydrolysis to open and close the clamp around the DNA.
- *Figure 5-18:* A bacterial replication fork. A single DNA polymerase molecule synthesizes the leading strand while two DNA polymerases are used in alternating fashion for lagging-strand synthesis; all polymerase molecules are held together at the fork by flexible protein tethers, forming a replisome complex.
- *Figure 5-19:* Schematic diagram of a eukaryotic replication fork. Unlike the bacterial replication proteins, those from eukaryotes function largely independently; the eukaryotic CMG helicase moves unidirectionally on the leading-strand template, and distinct DNA polymerases (Pol ε for leading strand, Pol δ for lagging strand) are used.
- *Figure 5-20:* Strand-directed mismatch repair in eukaryotes. The MutS protein binds to a mismatched base pair and recruits MutL; the complex scans nearby DNA for a gap and a sliding clamp whose orientation determines which strand is to be corrected; after identifying and excising the mismatch, DNA synthesis and ligation restore the sequence.
- *Figure 5-21:* The "winding problem" that arises during DNA replication. For a bacterial replication fork moving at 500 nucleotides per second, the parent DNA helix ahead of the fork must rotate at about 50 revolutions per second; tension builds up as the DNA becomes overwound, and DNA topoisomerases relieve this stress by generating temporary breaks.
- *Figure 5-22:* The reversible DNA nicking reaction catalyzed by a DNA topoisomerase I enzyme. These enzymes transiently form a single covalent bond with DNA, allowing free rotation around the covalent backbone bonds; on reversal, the enzyme also re-ligates the cut, changing the supercoiling state of the DNA without requiring ATP.
- *Figure 5-23:* The DNA-helix-passing reaction catalyzed by DNA topoisomerase II. Unlike type I topoisomerases, type II enzymes hydrolyze ATP to pass one double-stranded DNA segment through another, simultaneously changing the linking number by two and resolving tangles or supercoils.
- *Figure 5-24:* A replication bubble formed by replication-fork initiation. This diagram outlines the major steps in the initiation of replication forks at replication origins: initiator proteins bind and unwind DNA locally, loading helicases that allow bidirectional fork movement to create an expanding replication bubble.
- *Figure 5-25:* DNA replication of a bacterial genome. It takes E. coli about 30 minutes to duplicate its genome of 4.6 × 10⁶ nucleotide pairs, starting from a single origin of replication and proceeding bidirectionally until the two forks meet on the opposite side of the circular chromosome.
- *Figure 5-26:* The proteins that initiate DNA replication in bacteria. For E. coli, the major initiator protein DnaA, the DnaB helicase, and the DnaG primase cooperate at the oriC sequence to open the double helix, load the helicase, and begin synthesizing RNA primers that allow bidirectional replication to commence.
- *Figure 5-27:* Methylation of the E. coli replication origin creates a refractory period for DNA initiation. DNA methylation occurs at GATC sequences in the origin; immediately after replication, the origin is hemimethylated (one strand methylated) and is bound by a sequestration protein, preventing immediate re-initiation and ensuring that each origin fires only once per cell cycle.
- *Figure 5-28:* The experiments that first demonstrated the pattern in which replication forks are formed and move on eukaryotic chromosomes. Newly made DNA in human cells was labeled with a pulse of highly radioactive thymidine, revealing that DNA replication initiates at many origins simultaneously and that replication bubbles expand bidirectionally.
- *Figure 5-29:* The four successive phases of a standard eukaryotic cell cycle: G1, S, G2, and M phase. DNA replication is confined to S phase; the cell grows continuously during G1, S, and G2 phases; and chromosome segregation and cell division occur during M phase.
- *Figure 5-30:* The origins of DNA replication on chromosome III of the yeast S. cerevisiae. This small eukaryotic chromosome contains 18 replication origins used with different frequencies; origins used most often (in red) are distributed throughout the chromosome to ensure complete and timely replication.
- *Figure 5-31:* DNA replication initiation in eukaryotes. This mechanism ensures that each origin of replication is activated only once per cell cycle: Mcm helicases are loaded in G1 phase; at the start of S phase, specialized kinases phosphorylate and activate the helicases to form CMG complexes while also inactivating ORC to prevent re-loading until the next G1 phase.
- *Figure 5-32:* Formation of nucleosomes behind a replication fork. Parent H3–H4 tetramers remain associated with the fork and are distributed randomly to daughter DNA molecules; H2A–H2B dimers are released completely, then restored by histone chaperones (FACT, NAP1, CAF1) using both parent and newly synthesized histones to reconstitute chromatin.
- *Figure 5-33:* Schematic structure of human telomerase. This large enzyme is composed of 10 protein subunits and an RNA of 451 nucleotides; the RNA forms the scaffold of the complex, provides the template for synthesizing new telomeric DNA repeats, and the catalytic reaction is carried out by a reverse transcriptase subunit (TERT).
- *Figure 5-34:* Telomere replication. The 3′ end of the parent lagging-strand template is extended by RNA-templated DNA synthesis catalyzed by telomerase; this allows the incomplete daughter DNA strand that would otherwise shorten with each round of replication to be filled in, maintaining telomere length.
- *Figure 5-35:* A t-loop at the end of a mammalian chromosome. An electron micrograph and schematic diagram show that telomeric DNA folds back on itself to form a large protective loop (t-loop) where the single-stranded 3′ overhang invades the duplex region, preventing the chromosome end from being recognized as a double-strand break.
- *Figure 5-36:* A demonstration that yeast cells control the length of their telomeres. In this experiment, a telomere that was artificially made either longer or shorter than average returned to the normal average length after many cell divisions, demonstrating that cells actively monitor and regulate telomere length.
- *Figure 5-37:* A summary of spontaneous alterations that require DNA repair. The sites on each nucleotide modified by spontaneous oxidative damage, hydrolytic attack, and methylation are shown, with arrow widths indicating relative frequency; these data illustrate that DNA is under constant chemical attack requiring continuous repair surveillance.
- *Figure 5-38:* Depurination and deamination are the most frequent spontaneous chemical reactions known to create serious DNA damage in cells. Depurination removes guanine (or adenine) from DNA, creating an abasic site; deamination converts cytosine to uracil, which will mispair with adenine during replication, causing C-to-T transition mutations.
- *Figure 5-39:* The ultraviolet radiation in sunlight can cause the formation of thymine dimers. Two adjacent thymine bases become covalently attached to each other through a cyclobutane ring, distorting the DNA helix and blocking replication and transcription; skin cells are especially susceptible to this type of DNA damage.
- *Figure 5-40:* Chemical modifications of nucleotides, if left unrepaired, produce mutations. Deamination of cytosine produces uracil, which pairs with adenine rather than guanine, converting a C-G base pair to a T-A base pair; deamination of methylated cytosine produces thymine, which is not immediately recognized as an error, making this a hotspot for mutations.
- *Figure 5-41:* A comparison of two major DNA repair pathways. Base excision repair starts with a DNA glycosylase that removes the damaged base, creating an abasic site that is then processed by AP endonuclease, filled in by DNA polymerase, and sealed by ligase; nucleotide excision repair uses a different strategy to cut out and replace a short oligonucleotide patch containing the damaged base.
- *Figure 5-42:* The recognition of an unusual nucleotide in DNA by base-flipping. The DNA glycosylase family of enzymes flips the target base out of the double helix into the enzyme's active site where it is cleaved from the sugar backbone, allowing the enzyme to access damaged bases without fully unwinding the DNA.
- *Figure 5-43:* The deamination of DNA nucleotides. Deamination of A and G produces unnatural bases (hypoxanthine and xanthine) that are readily recognized and repaired; deamination of C produces uracil (repaired by uracil-DNA glycosylase), but deamination of 5-methylcytosine produces thymine, which is much harder to recognize as wrong because thymine is a normal DNA base.
- *Figure 5-44:* How translesion DNA polymerases are recruited to damaged templates. When a replicative polymerase stalls at a site of DNA damage, the sliding clamp is ubiquitylated; this modified clamp recruits specialized translesion synthesis (TLS) polymerases that have larger, more open active sites and can synthesize past many types of DNA lesions, albeit with lower fidelity.
- *Figure 5-45:* Cells can repair double-strand breaks in one of two ways. In nonhomologous end joining (NHEJ), the break is cleaned and ligated directly, often causing small deletions; in homologous recombination (HR), an intact homologous sequence serves as a template for accurate repair, which is especially important in S and G2 phases when a sister chromatid is available.
- *Figure 5-46:* Nonhomologous end joining. The Ku heterodimer protein quickly grasps the broken chromosome ends; additional proteins are then recruited to hold the broken ends together, remove damaged nucleotides, and ligate the two DNA molecules, often resulting in the loss of a few nucleotides at the break site.
- *Figure 5-47:* A mechanism that repairs double-strand breaks by homologous recombination. After a double-strand break, a nuclease generates 3′ single-stranded overhangs; the RecA/Rad51 protein coats these overhangs and catalyzes strand invasion into an intact homologous duplex, priming DNA synthesis that uses the undamaged molecule as a template for accurate repair.
- *Figure 5-48:* Strand invasion catalyzed by the RecA protein. Structures determined by x-ray diffraction show the RecA nucleoprotein filament bound to single-stranded and double-stranded DNA; the protein aligns the single-stranded DNA with the homologous region of the duplex and catalyzes the exchange of strands, a central step in homologous recombination.
- *Figure 5-49:* Repair of a broken replication fork by homologous recombination. When a moving replication fork encounters a single-strand break, the fork collapses into a double-strand break; homologous recombination using the intact sister chromatid as template restores the fork and allows replication to resume.
- *Figure 5-50:* Repair of a stalled replication fork by "fork reversal." When a replication fork stalls at certain types of damaged nucleotides, a specialized helicase peels back the newly synthesized strands to form a "chicken foot" structure; this reversal allows the damage to be repaired before the fork is restarted.
- *Figure 5-51:* Experiment demonstrating the rapid localization of repair proteins to DNA double-strand breaks. Human fibroblasts were x-irradiated through a microscopic grid, producing DNA double-strand breaks in defined linear tracks; within minutes, repair proteins (shown by immunofluorescence) concentrate precisely at the damage sites, demonstrating the cell's rapid damage-sensing and repair-protein recruitment capability.
- *Figure 5-52:* Chromosome crossing-over occurs in meiosis. Meiosis produces germ cells in which paternal and maternal genetic information has been reassorted through chromosome crossovers (recombination), increasing genetic diversity. The diagram shows how homologous chromosomes pair, exchange segments, and segregate to form haploid gametes.
- *Figure 5-53:* Homologous recombination during meiosis can generate chromosome crossovers. After the Spo11 complex creates a double-strand break, homologous recombination can proceed along alternative pathways: one generates crossovers (chiasmata) that hold homologs together until chromosome segregation; the other produces non-crossovers through synthesis-dependent strand annealing.
- *Figure 5-54:* A Holliday junction. The initially formed structure can isomerize into an open, symmetrical structure bound by specialized proteins; these proteins "move" the Holliday junction along the DNA (branch migration) and eventually resolve it by cutting either pair of strands, producing either crossover or non-crossover products.
- *Figure 5-55:* Enzyme-catalyzed branch movement at a Holliday junction by branch migration. A tetramer of RuvA protein (green) and two hexamers of RuvB protein (yellow) bind to the open junction; RuvB acts as a DNA-dependent ATPase motor that drives branch migration in the direction of RuvB movement, extending the region of heteroduplex DNA.
- *Figure 5-56:* Heteroduplexes formed during meiosis. Heteroduplex DNA is present at sites of recombination resolved either as crossovers or non-crossovers; because maternal and paternal DNA sequences differ at many positions, heteroduplexes often contain mismatched base pairs that are subject to mismatch repair.
- *Figure 5-57:* Gene conversion caused by mismatch correction. Heteroduplex DNA formed during recombination may contain mismatches; mismatch repair proteins correct these mismatches by excising one strand and replacing it with a copy of the other, converting the DNA sequence from one parental type to the other (gene conversion) without a crossover.
- *Figure 5-58:* Transposons often code for the components they need for transposition. Two types of bacterial DNA-only transposons are shown, each carrying a gene encoding a transposase—the enzyme that catalyzes movement—as well as short terminal inverted repeat sequences that are recognized by the transposase.
- *Figure 5-59:* Cut-and-paste transposition. DNA-only transposons are recognized in chromosomes by inverted repeat DNA sequences at their ends; the transposase cuts the transposon out of the donor DNA at both ends and inserts it into a new target site through a staggered cut, creating short direct repeats flanking the element at the new location.
- *Figure 5-60:* Mechanism of transposition by helitrons, a type of DNA-only transposon. The helitron transposase (Helraiser from bats) has a helicase domain and a replication-initiation domain; it nicks the transposon 3′ end, uses a rolling-circle mechanism to copy the transposon into a new genomic location, and captures the new site by pairing between single-stranded sequences.
- *Figure 5-61:* The life cycle of a retrovirus. The retrovirus genome consists of an RNA molecule packaged inside a protein capsid; after infection, reverse transcriptase converts the viral RNA into double-stranded DNA, which integrates into the host chromosome as a provirus; the provirus is then transcribed by the host's RNA polymerase to produce new viral proteins and genomic RNA.
- *Figure 5-62:* Simplified view of the coronavirus life cycle as exemplified by SARS-CoV-2. The single-strand RNA genome is directly translated into protein after entering the cytoplasm; a viral RNA-dependent RNA polymerase (replicase) then produces complementary copies of the genome, which serve as templates for new genomes; structural proteins and new genomes assemble and bud from host membranes to form new virions.
- *Figure 5-63:* Transposition by a nonretroviral retrotransposon (L1 element). An endonuclease nicks the target DNA; the L1 RNA is then reverse-transcribed directly at the nick site by a mechanism called target-primed reverse transcription (TPRT), inserting the new DNA copy into the genome without first producing a DNA intermediate in the cytoplasm.
- *Figure 5-64:* Two types of DNA rearrangement produced by conservative site-specific recombination. The difference between integration/excision (A) and DNA inversion (B) lies in the relative orientation of the two short recombination sites; same-orientation sites on different or the same molecule produce integration or deletion, while inverted sites on the same molecule produce inversion.
- *Figure 5-65:* Switching gene expression by DNA inversion in bacteria (Salmonella phase variation). Which flagellin gene is expressed is controlled by a conservative site-specific recombination event that inverts a small DNA segment containing a promoter; inversion places either flagellin gene H1 or H2 under promoter control, allowing the bacterium to alternate between two antigenic surface types.
- *Figure 5-66:* How a conservative site-specific recombination enzyme from bacteria is used to delete a specific gene from a particular mouse tissue. Two engineered DNA molecules are introduced into the germ line: one contains the gene for a recombinase (Cre) under tissue-specific promoter control; the other contains the gene of interest flanked by the recombinase's target sites (loxP); recombinase expression causes precise deletion of the floxed gene only in the target tissue.
